INSERT INTO `pages` VALUES (107,'kevinvennemann','kevinvennemann','No Country For Odd Poets: Kevin Vennemann','No Country For Odd Poets: Kevin Vennemann','','<p class=\"times-large\"><strong>Kevin Vennemann</strong></p>\r\n<p class=\"times-large\">Reading on Tuesday 21 May 2013, 8pm</p>\r\n<p>Kevin Vennemann is a German author and is the youngest guest in the No Coutry For Odd Poets series to date. His first novel <em>Nahe Jedenew</em>, published in 2005 by Suhrkamp Verlag gained critical acclaim. Helmut Böttiger from Deutschland Radio Kultur describing it as, \'one of the best novels by an under 30-year old over the last few years’. <em>Nahe Jedenew</em> tells the story of two Jewish-German girls during the Second World War whose family become victims of the Pogrom. Hidden away, up in a treehouse they observe the destruction of their home whilst attempting to seek refuge in stories from their past.</p>\r\n<p>In his most recent novel <em>Sunset Boulevard: Vom Filmen, Bauen und Sterben in Los Angeleshe</em> poses the question as to how far the The Modern Project in architecture was thwarted by the aestheticization of Julius Schulman\'s class-hierarchical stereotypes and thus was kept from the masses. The invisible death and the sordid lack of history and face is the subject of Vennemann\'s foray.</p>\r\n<p>Felix Stephan from the newspaper Süddeutsche Zeitung described the novel as being, \'such a great success, because it genuinely manages to introduce a new form of writing. Vennemann manages to take a literary historical step which post-modernism regarded as an impossibility; this being due to their never questioning the institution of \'the novel\'. Kevin Vennemann goes one step further, wherein he presupposes, that for fiction, literature is not necessary - the world is sufficient enough.\'</p>\r\n<p>Coincidentally, our previous guest Chris Kraus appears as a prominent figure in <em>Sunset Boulevard</em>. She accompanies him on his odyssey throughout the novel. Since several years Kraus and Vennemann have had a close relationship as colleagues and friends.</p>\r\n<p>Further literary works by Kevin Vennemann are his novel <em>Mara Kogoj</em> (2007) and most recently his translation of <em>Bluescreen</em> by the American essayist Mark Greif. </p>',106,0,'[[{\"type\":\"imagegallery\",\"id\":582},0,{\"type\":\"imagegallery\",\"id\":623}],[0,{\"type\":\"imagegallery\",\"id\":622},{\"type\":\"basetext\"}],[{\"type\":\"imagegallery\",\"id\":620},{\"type\":\"imagegallery\",\"id\":621},0]]','<div id=\"container\" style=\"position: absolute; top: 0px; left: 0px; width: 2501px; height: 3064px; \"><div style=\"position: absolute; top: 1074px; left: 1937px; width: 470px; height: 1240px; \">\n            <h1 class=\"basetext\"><img src=\"/hlimages/106.jpeg\" alt=\"No Country For Odd Poets: Kevin Vennemann\"></h1>\n            <div>\n      \n          </div>\n  \n</div><div style=\"position: absolute; top: 91px; left: 91px; width: 839px; height: 802px; \"><ul class=\"imagegallery\"><li><a href=\"/images/856.jpeg\">Bild</a></li></ul></div><div style=\"position: absolute; top: 91px; left: 1932px; width: 480px; height: 640px; \"><ul class=\"imagegallery\"><li><a href=\"/images/904.jpeg\">Bild</a></li></ul></div><div style=\"position: absolute; top: 1074px; left: 1111px; width: 600px; height: 480px; \"><ul class=\"imagegallery\"><li><a href=\"/images/892.jpeg\">Bild</a></li><li><a href=\"/images/893.jpeg\">Bild</a></li><li><a href=\"/images/895.jpeg\">Bild</a></li><li><a href=\"/images/896.jpeg\">Bild</a></li><li><a href=\"/images/897.jpeg\">Bild</a></li><li><a href=\"/images/898.jpeg\">Bild</a></li><li><a href=\"/images/899.jpeg\">Bild</a></li><li><a href=\"/images/902.jpeg\">Bild</a></li><li><a href=\"/images/903.jpeg\">Bild</a></li></ul></div><div style=\"position: absolute; top: 2495px; left: 91px; width: 432px; height: 281px; \"><ul class=\"imagegallery\"><li><a href=\"/images/889.png\">Bild</a></li></ul></div><div style=\"position: absol